# Testing Conventions

## File Organization
- Colocate test files with their source: `users.service.ts` -> `users.service.test.ts`
- Use `.test.ts` for unit tests and `.spec.ts` for integration tests
- Place shared test utilities in `src/test/helpers.ts`
- Place test fixtures in `src/test/fixtures/` as plain TypeScript objects

## Test Structure
- Use descriptive `describe` blocks named after the function or module under test
- Use `it` (not `test`) with descriptions that read as sentences: `it('returns 404 when user not found')`
- Follow Arrange-Act-Assert pattern with blank lines separating each phase
- Keep each test focused on a single behavior — avoid testing multiple things at once

## Assertions
- Prefer `expect(x).toBe(y)` for primitives and `expect(x).toEqual(y)` for objects
- Use `toMatchObject` for partial object matching in API response tests
- Use `toThrow` or `rejects.toThrow` for error path testing
- Avoid snapshot tests for API responses — use explicit assertions

## Mocking
- Use `vi.mock()` at the top of the file for module-level mocks
- Prefer dependency injection over mocking when possible
- Reset all mocks in `beforeEach` with `vi.clearAllMocks()`
- Use `vi.spyOn` for observing calls without replacing implementation
- Type mock return values explicitly — never let mocks return `undefined` silently

## API Testing
- Use `supertest` with the Express app instance for HTTP integration tests
- Test all response status codes, not just the happy path
- Verify response body structure matches the expected `{ data }` or `{ error, code }` format
- Test authentication and authorization separately from business logic

## Coverage
- Aim for >80% line coverage on service and utility modules
- Do not test trivial getters, type definitions, or re-exports
- Focus coverage on branching logic, error paths, and edge cases
